J.T. It synchronises with it; so that @Romans 8 properly links on with Ephesians. In the type as we have it in Samuel, Jehovah says, "I will be his father": that comes out at the Lord's baptism and on the mount of transfiguration -- "and he shall be my son" (@2 Samuel 7: 14). Where is that answered to? Where *can* it be answered to more fully than in the assembly? "He shall be my son": that is what He is Godward; and the Spirit of adoption in us places us alongside of Him. *What* a Son the Father has in Him! The result of that communication is that David goes in and sits before the Lord: it is the inwardness of the thing. He tarries there; there is no need for him to go out. The inward thought is that the nearer I get the freer and the more at home I am. The more free I am in sonship, the more the Lord can express what He is to the Father: "*he* shall be to me for son" (@Hebrews 1: 5).
